The Objections
--------------

One lesson that we tend to painfully learn again and again is that there ar=
e a lot of regulatory initiatives that are created with good intentions and=
 which make logical sense, but which end up being counterproductive and/or =
having problematic second and third order consequences. To that end, I see =
three big issues with these new rules, above-and-beyond the long-term Ameri=
can competitiveness point noted above.

First, as I noted, these rules are long and onerous, and are going to entai=
l a massive amount of compliance costs and a reduction in velocity. This wa=
s the core of Oracle=E2=80=99s objections ( https://www.oracle.com/news/ann=
ouncement/blog/export-control-diffusion-confusion-2025-01-05/ ) :

The Framework introduces so many new acronyms in what we may better call th=
e Confusion Framework that it=E2=80=99s hard to keep them straight: AIA, AC=
M, LPP, DC VEU, UVEU, NVEU, TPP, ACA. Then the Framework identifies 20 AIA =
countries (Artificial Intelligence Authorization Countries) for modestly be=
tter regulatory treatment than the rest of the world, but at the same time =
creates a regulatory morass for cloud providers to even service some of our=
 closest allies. In a single confusing action, the BIS retroactively regula=
tes global cloud GPU deployments; shrinks the global market for U.S. cloud =
and chip suppliers; establishes volume restrictions; tells 20 countries the=
y can be trusted only if they agree to new unilaterally imposed terms=E2=80=
=94including certification and semi-annual reporting requirements=E2=80=94a=
nd likely pushes the rest of the world to Chinese technology, which the CCP=
 will be only too happy to leverage to catch up with the U.S.

Next, the Framework sets up UVEUs (Universal Validated End Users). These ar=
e apparently trusted ultimate consignees (i.e. U.S. cloud hyperscalers) tha=
t will enjoy faster access to provide GPUs worldwide. The problem with UVEU=
s is they come with strings attached =E2=80=A6 actually, the regulation sha=
ckles UVEUs to the BIS in perpetuity. The UVEU program is tethered to FedRA=
MP High (plus a series of NIST standards), a U.S. government-defined collec=
tion of information and physical security requirements =E2=80=9Cto account =
for the government=E2=80=99s most sensitive, unclassified data in cloud com=
puting environments=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94not commercial industry data.=
v FedRAMP High requires annual third-party audits, specific staffing and ac=
cess controls, and it includes data sovereignty requirements, mandating U.S=
. locations for storage of U.S. government data. The problem is that outsid=
e of the U.S. (and even for the overwhelming majority of data centers insid=
e the U.S.), there is no reason for the thousands of existing commercial da=
ta centers to meet these requirements, and they currently do not. The UVEU =
process would fundamentally change the economics of data center deployment =
around the world. Having been through the FedRAMP High process, it is not f=
or the faint of heart.

Keep in mind, this is Oracle of all companies complaining about paperwork a=
nd compliance costs. Sure, in the long run this burden will favor the large=
st companies, but it will be a huge pain in the rear end, slow down deploym=
ents, and catch a lot of legitimate businesses and use cases in its net. In=
 this it reminds me of the net neutrality debate ( https://stratechery.com/=
2017/pro-neutrality-anti-title-ii/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZ=
CI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJ=
hdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIi=
wiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE3L3Byby1uZXV0cmFsa=
XR5LWFudGktdGl0bGUtaWkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3Mzk0NTIwMTQsImlhdCI6MTczNjg2MDAxNCwi=
aXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJ=
lYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLC=
JzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.ma1uyP1N5ruNu=
LCHM2h1O7Os6plYcLb7uYA2om6m98YFNEnudKq5v-zQFeOT-SRXO76gcRc2-mjR6XEhbQzqtNHH=
gGsuv6bvNiO81AuiV66Rpl3a-9OIFLWV2jn5FadV6rch96WwPnkXc2Slc59Q8jig6eF5gnVsqPe=
phXgTRB8EGmmUGKzjt_aHKYZAZsDI9bv1m1vE6RKJEh4MUK19EaFchllexFxg66dl09n1VJlSB7=
3F-ubfWdWMp-jMmTnsJWlip-LHdD1_isfPFJ51BoSs0rjSTSd52w4y4csc-5q4x2o0g6BVBQvUo=
PfU_xlfnDyc-7oMGdfKrifBnpEWHw ) : my objection to Title II was not because =
I was opposed to net neutrality, but rather that I recognized the tremendou=
s costs and ultimate limitations in availability and velocity that accompan=
y bureaucratic processes ill-suited to the task at hand (in this case rules=
 designed to limit China that end up applied to every single AI use case ar=
ound the world).

Secondly, and along those lines, this introduces a fundamentally new paradi=
gm to U.S. tech regulation. Until now the U.S. has operated with a presumpt=
ion of openness, with targeted controls on various technologies (which have=
 changed and evolved over time). Yes, this allows stuff to slip through the=
 cracks, but defaulting to openness means defaulting to innovation and worl=
dwide expansion, which undergirds the U.S. tech industry=E2=80=99s worldwid=
e dominance. To put it in legal terms, tech has operated in an =E2=80=9Cinn=
ocent until proven guilty=E2=80=9D paradigm.

These regulations, however, change that around: now GPU purchasers are guil=
ty until proven innocent. Exports, and all of the innovation and expansion =
that follows, need permission by default. This will not only slow things do=
wn, but critically, it also sets the stage for similar intrusions into tech=
 markets in the future.

Back in 2021 I wrote an Article called Apple=E2=80=99s Mistake ( https://st=
ratechery.com/2021/apples-mistake/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZ=
CI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJ=
hdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIi=
wiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL2FwcGxlcy1taXN0Y=
WtlLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzM5NDUyMDE0LCJpYXQiOjE3MzY4NjAwMTQsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8v=
YXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmV=
hZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOG=
